<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-position-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Position Vectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_rdmjaf3v">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_kj58qcia">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_dk7h2cjm">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6mv1eau6">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_v4m1i2jx">
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_vpni0hqo">
                <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_t8goecs1">Determine translation vector as a transformation</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tl672gly" component="lesson-plan">
                <title>Grade Level</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_na221j1e">Grade 10</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8p8qjr9o" component="lesson-plan">
                <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_u9vahhmm">40 minutes</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p xml:id="auto_peq24gqg" component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>By the end of this lesson, learners should be able to:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ncwgn67n" component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Know:</alert> The definition of a position vector as a vector from the origin to a specific point in the plane.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xzd6n6st" component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Do:</alert> Determine position vectors of given points; distinguish between position vectors and displacement vectors.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_y52tyvjh" component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Apply:</alert> Use position vectors to describe locations relative to a reference point in navigation and GPS contexts.
        </p>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_89hik6rl">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/position-vectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_c3nv3z6z">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_position-vectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_if5o5mm1">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Organize students into groups of 2–3.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_l2dh3qa6">
            <alert>Materials:</alert> Graph paper, rulers, pencils, coloured markers.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_idq42zjd">
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_971vl4te">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_yg72jv7h">Circulate among students, ensuring they plot points correctly.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_17fp7f87">Ask probing questions: <q>Where is the origin? What is the position of point A?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g8khhyq6">For struggling students: <q>Let us draw the line from O to A together. What are the coordinates of A?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zevsb65w">For early finishers: <q>Can you find the position vectors of points C and D?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_z59pfxq8">Guide students to articulate: a position vector starts from the origin and points to a specific location.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qzyyr1kg">Identify 2–3 students with clear findings to share with the class.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_j57at4pq">
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vwzhsngs">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_0qazkgfv"><q>What is the position of point A relative to the origin?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3yae2q5a"><q>How do we write the position vector of A?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dqdryvyx"><q>What is the difference between a position vector and a regular vector?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dlmv75bo"><q>Can you think of real-world examples where we describe position relative to a starting point?</q></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_8uv0nuv3">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_ztgw2xh2">
            <p xml:id="auto_6342te8i">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_e15h65yg">
                <alert>What you require: </alert> Graph paper
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_q93wwlez">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_bus2bj9u">
                    Draw the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axis on the graph paper as shown below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                            \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-6,-6) grid (6,6);

                            % Draw main grid (original)
                            \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-6,-6) grid (6,6);

                            % Draw axes
                            \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (-5.5,0) -- (5.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                            \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (0,-5.5) -- (0,5.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                            % Label x-axis
                            \foreach \x in {-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5} {
                                \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                            }

                            % Label y-axis
                            \foreach \y in {-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5} {
                                \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                            }
                            \node[below] at (-0.2,-0.2) {0};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_xzop360q">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_9sjq4vt5">
                    Plot the following points <m>A(1,1),B(3,5),C(2,1),D(4,-3) </m> on the graph.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_u4iuikun">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6yieuin8">
                    Draw a directed line from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> to represent <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_dg0ef3m3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_20nnl4cy">
                    Draw another directed line from <m>D</m> to <m>C</m> to represent <m>\overrightarrow{CD}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_hpnog3dg">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_55bgesd8">
                     Determine the position vector of <m>B</m> relative to point <m>A</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_s0tb0hwd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_f0ikg7mn">
                    Determine the position vector of <m>C</m> relative to point <m>D</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_llrp26kj">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_w3efpqa9">
                    Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_xgnxcb45">
        <p xml:id="auto_v1vjll1l">
            In <xref ref="illustration-position-vector-1"/> below, points <m>A(2,3)</m> and 
            <m>B(5,1)</m> are located in the plane relative to origin point O in the plane.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wu4xg6fb">
            The position vector of <m>A</m> is <m>\textbf{OA} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 - 0 \\ 3 - 0 \end{pmatrix} = \binom{2}{3}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_g2rzb4tg">
            The position vector of <m>B</m> is <m>\textbf{OB} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 - 0 \\ 1 - 0 \end{pmatrix} = \binom{5}{1}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_d63bxjht">
            Similarly, for point <m>A</m> in the plane its position vector <m>\textbf{OA}</m>
            is denoted by <m>\mathbf{a}</m>. Also for point <m>B</m> in the plane it's position vector 
            <m>\textbf{OB}</m> is denoted by <m>\mathbf{b}</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="illustration-position-vector-1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="45%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="examp-position-vector">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                    \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-3,-3) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw main grid (original)
                    \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-3,-3) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw axes
                    \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (6.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                    \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0,5.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                    % Label x-axis
                    \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                        \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                    }

                    % Label y-axis
                    \foreach \y in {1,2,3,4,5} {
                        \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                    }
                    \node[below] at (0,-0.1) {0};

                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (1.3,1.96) -- (1.31,1.98);
                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (2.4,0.48) -- (2.45,0.49);

                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (A) at (2,3);
                    \coordinate (B) at (5,1);

                    % Draw vectors
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (A) node[midway, left] {\small $\mathbf{a}$};
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (B) node[midway, below] {\small $\mathbf{b}$};
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);

                    % Label points
                    \node[above left] at (A) {\small A(2,3)};
                    \node[right] at (B) {\small B(5,1)};
                    \node[above left] at (-0.1,-0.1) {\large O(0,0)};

                \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_uml5zh03">
            After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalize the concept of position vectors.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_d3y7cyxn">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_s98copbn">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_zpwz0fv3"><alert>Misconception:</alert> Position vectors can start from any point. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Position vectors always start from the origin <m>O(0,0)</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lfb6g3di"><alert>Misconception:</alert> Position vector is the same as the point. <alert>Clarification:</alert> A point is a location; a position vector describes movement from the origin to that location.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_snmkwnwi"><alert>Misconception:</alert> I need to perform a subtraction. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Since the origin is <m>(0,0)</m>, subtracting zero gives the point coordinates directly.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zjoyi0jc"><alert>Misconception:</alert> Position vectors are different from column vectors. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Position vectors are written using column vector notation.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_3jy2p35x">
            Guide students through the worked example below, then assign independent practice.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_le1s7n7p">
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lw5dz9we">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_zmg125gq">Remind students that the position vector of <m>P(x,y)</m> is simply <m>\binom{x}{y}</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8kmh63kd">Have students read coordinates from the graph before writing the vector.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jrva6tqn">Point out that position vectors in different quadrants will have negative components.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_k8qizai7">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_qn1zsef9">
                Find the position vector of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
            </p>
            <image width="80%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="example-position-vector">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                    \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-5,-5) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw main grid (original)
                    \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-5,-5) grid (7,6);

                    % Draw axes
                    \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (6.5,0) node[right] {\small $x$};
                    \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5.5) node[above] {\small $y$};

                    % Label x-axis
                    \foreach \x in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                        \draw (\x,0.2) -- (\x,-0.2) node[below] {\small \x};
                    }

                    % Label y-axis
                    \foreach \y in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5} {
                        \draw (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left]{\small \y};
                    }
                    \node[below] at (-0.2,-0.1) {0};
                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (3.4,-1.12) -- (3.5,-1.15);
                    \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (1.9,-1.9) -- (2,-2);

                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (A) at (6,-2);
                    \coordinate (B) at (4,-4);

                    % Draw vectors
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (A) node[midway, above] {\small $\mathbf{a}$};
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (B) node[midway, below] {\small $\mathbf{b}$};
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);

                    % Label points
                    \node[right] at (A) {\small A};
                    \node[below] at (B) {\small B};
                    \node[above left] at (0,-0.1) {\small O(0,0)};

                \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_pi6sj5nf">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hqlpgdv9">
                The position vector of A is <m>\textbf{OA } = \begin{pmatrix} 6 - 0 \\ -2 - 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 6  \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_13z5s7fu">
                Similarly the position vector of B is <m> \textbf{OB }= \begin{pmatrix} 4 - 0 \\ -4 - 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4  \\ -4 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_ak3u07b1">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_efucapbs">
                The points <m>A(1,2)</m>, <m>B(7,4)</m> and <m>C(3,10)</m> lie in the Cartesian plane.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6qk3v1h1">
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ty0scqkd">
                        <p xml:id="auto_kfyyvtv3">
                            Find the coordinates of point <m>D</m> which divides <m>BC</m> internally in the ratio <m>2:1</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_imtgjgpd">
                        <p xml:id="auto_h50iujnn">
                            Find the coordinates of point <m>E</m>, the midpoint of <m>AD</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_cixu4x68">
                        <p xml:id="auto_h5fcnklt">
                            Show that <m>A</m>, <m>E</m> and the centroid of triangle <m>ABC</m> are collinear.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_r3nm0lxp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vqjwwbox">
                             Find the area of triangle <m>AEC</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_09cd2kum">
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ehepqhgm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_zaz5k2yb">
                            Since <m>D</m> divides <m>BC</m> internally in the ratio <m>2:1</m>,
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_mj2euxyd">
                            <m>D = \frac{2C + 1B}{3}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_tabojvsn">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>D =  \amp \frac{2(3,10) + (7,4)}{3}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{(6,20) + (7,4)}{3}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{(13,24)}{3}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_fiqgadk4">
                            <m>D\left(\frac{13}{3},8\right)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bic3sm43">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ba7hwzk5">
                            Since <m>E</m> is the midpoint of <m>AD</m>,
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_fmy7lejd">
                            <m>E = \frac{A + D}{2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3d3p25i9">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> E = \amp \frac{\left(1,2\right) + \left(\frac{13}{3},8\right)}{2}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{\left(\frac{16}{3},10\right)}{2}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_rmg1da3s">
                            <m>E\left(\frac{8}{3},5\right)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_d74aiw7u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_l3yly97h">
                            The centroid <m>G</m> of triangle <m>ABC</m> is
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_0p2sn4b4">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> G = \amp \frac{A + B + C}{3}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{(1,2) + (7,4) + (3,10)}{3}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{(11,16)}{3}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_8cc2lhtw">
                            <m>G\left(\frac{11}{3}, \frac{16}{3}\right)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_zrzvh06q">
                            Now consider vectors:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_pwf963gz">
                            <m>\vec{AE} = \left(\frac{8}{3}-1, 5-2\right) = \left(\frac{5}{3},3\right)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_75p8vd2x">
                            <m>\vec{AG} = \left(\frac{11}{3}-1, \frac{16}{3}-2\right) = \left(\frac{8}{3}, \frac{10}{3}\right)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_18k42z5e">
                            <m>\vec{AG} \ne x \vec{AE}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_18gtz5tv">
                            Therefore, the vectors are not scalar multiples, hence <m>A</m>, <m>E</m> and <m>G</m> are not collinear.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_3572gmed">
                        <p xml:id="auto_xax60y1v">
                            Area of triangle <m>AEC</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_hl8kh5v2">
                           Use Surveyor's Formula: 
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_1ugss5gm">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{1}{2} \left| x_1(y_2 - y_3) + x_2(y_3 - y_1) + x_3(y_1 - y_2) \right| </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \left|1 \times -\frac{1}{3} + \frac{8}{3} \times \frac{10}{3} + \frac{11}{3} \right| \times -3 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \left| -\frac{1}{3} + \frac{80}{9} -11 \right|</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times \frac{22}{9}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{11}{9}</mrow> 
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_yniynsv8">
                            Therefore, the area of triangle <m>AEC</m> is <m>\frac{11}{9}</m> square units.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket (5 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_3db91xfj">
            Students complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_uwsbyfo8">
